City of Cape Town law enforcement evicted several hundred people from open ground they had occupied over the easter weekend. Khayelitsha Cape Town COVID-19 lockdown, 14 April 2020. (Photo: David Harrison) The legal question to be urgently considered by the Western Cape High Court on Friday 17 April includes whether an eviction order obtained by the City of Cape Town in 2018 can be enforced against a different set of people. The added â€“ and perhaps decisive â€“ complication is the current State of Disaster that seems to prohibit all demolitions and evictions. Where do you go when the government on the one hand breaks down your home and on the other enforces Covid 19-regulations allowing one to be arrested for not being at home, disheartened residents asked. To defend its conduct, described as â€œconstitutionally and legally abhorrentâ€, the City of Cape Town told its citizens that it had effected â€œno evictionsâ€ and had only demolished â€œunoccupied and incomplete structuresâ€. Their dilemma, in part, will be to explain away the video footage of Khayelitsha residents and journalists on the scene showing fully built and occupied structures complete with couches, stoves, cupboards and pit toilets. *** â€œCome, look here. This was my table.â€ We are standing on a barren, godforsaken piece of land in Khayelitsha next to Baden Powell Drive. It is 4pm on a Tuesday in April, the 19th day of South Africaâ€™s coronavirus lockdown. Whatâ€™s left of Selby Kolossaâ€™s table is half-hidden under debris which on Thursday was the door to his home. â€œThis was my pit toilet. Look. Can you see?â€  I have so many questions, but Kolossa insists, willing me to focus on the â€œcrime sceneâ€ at his feet. It took many hours to dig that pit toilet. â€œLook.â€ He speaks over my questions. â€œThis was my food cupboard. I had potatoes in here.â€ The cupboard is on its back in the Cape Flatsâ€™ dirty, powdery white sand, a single door left on its hinges. One by one he points to and identifi