said they were not violent and sang Struggle songs in front of the officials. When asked by Daily Maverick whether the Cityâ€™s officials were met with any violence from the community, the Mayco member for human settlements, Malusi Booi, said: â€œYes, at times. In addition, remember also that these members of the public were performing illegal acts of land invasion as well as in contravention of the national Covid-19 lockdown.â€ The City attempted to support and justify its hard-handed act with a press statement this week stating it had to deal with 16 known attempted land invasions since the national lockdown on 26 March. (See the full response here) â€œThe City is not evicting anyone,â€ Booi claimed, â€œâ€¦only unoccupied and incomplete structures are being removed. â€œThe illegal occupation of vacant land during this period may have dire consequences. These illegal settlements have no access to services, which is a great concern because of the serious health and hygiene, fire, flood and safety risks. â€œThe City does not have the capacity to manage unplanned and unbudgeted settlements at the expense of existing settlementsâ€¦. this also has a detrimental effect on the Cityâ€™s mandate to provide housing to its most vulnerable residents and rightful beneficiaries.â€ If the City of Cape Townâ€™s goal was to remove residents from the site, the exercise was completely ineffective. â€œWhere must we go and what should we do?â€ resident Mthozami Xaka, 44, asked when Daily Maverick visited this week. â€œWe are told we cannot work because there is this Covid virus. Everyone must stay inside. How will we do that now?â€ Destitute men and women now sleep under the stars where their homes once were, increasing their chances of falling ill and burdening the hospitals in their neighbourhood at a time these facilities cannot afford it. Pregnant women and women with children pleaded for lodgings at their neighbours and friends. Cape Town weather took a turn for the worse over the