nduct as â€œconstitutionally and legally abhorrentâ€. The LRC asks the court to declare that the demolition and the removal of residentsâ€™ building materials and personal belongings was unlawful and unconstitutional. The residents ask that the City of Cape Town return their materials and personal possessions or provide each household with the equivalent alternative building materials and R2,000 per occupant as compensation. The residents further want to remain on the land until the lockdown has ended and until the City obtained a lawful eviction order under the Unlawful Occupation of Land Act. The LRC further argues that anyone removed from their homes is acutely vulnerable to the health risks posed by the coronavirus, and to render people homeless would â€œdefeat the purpose of the regulationsâ€. The destructive behaviour of its officials may pose a problem to the Cityâ€™s argument. â€œLaw Enforcement were not only breaking down houses, they vandalised our belongings,â€ another resident Makhasa Mpolweni, 47, told Daily Maverick. â€œWe were trying to negotiate with them,â€ Mpolweni said, â€œasking if we can resolve the matter any other way. I was talking to closed ears. Some essential workers were at work. When they came back, there was nothing left.â€ The Western Cape High Court instructed the City in 2018 that all possessions and building materials of demolished houses â€œshall be kept in safe custody for three weeksâ€ until released to the lawful owner. Khayelitsha residents report merciless and callous destruction. So much so, Mpolweni said, that he only managed to salvage his South African identification document from the debris of his house five days after it was demolished. â€œI wasnâ€™t allowed to save anything,â€ he claimed. The second challenge the City of Cape Town will face is its assertion that it demolished only â€œunoccupied and incomplete structuresâ€ and did not conduct any â€œevictionsâ€. In its court papers, the City claimed that â€œâ€¦none of th